component.valueString: Widening of the aortic arch diameter to 4.5cm or greater or the descending aorta to 4cm or greater, typically due to aneurysm, dissection or rupture.
Widening of the aortic curve while maintaining a normal aortic diameter.
Calcification of the aortic arch. Does not include mitral valve calcification, descending aortic or pericardial calcification. Only includes Grade 2 or 3 calcification i.e. thick calcification.
Single area of consolidation or air space / ground glass opacity in the lung. Air bronchogram may be present.
Multiple area of ill defined airspace  / ground glass opacity or consolidation.
Diffuse ill-defined airspace  / ground glass opacity or consolidation throughout one or both lungs.

note.text: Diffuse lower airspace opacity is absent

component.valueString: Diffuse ill-defined airspace / ground glass opacity or consolidation in predominantly the lower zones of one or both lungs. Does not include interstitial opacities. This finding may still be predicted if there are upper zone changes as long as the pattern is lower zone predominant.

note.text: Diffuse upper airspace opacity is absent

component.valueString: Diffuse ill-defined airspace / ground glass opacity or consolidation in predominantly the upper zones of one or both lungs. Does not include interstitial opacities. This finding may still be predicted if there are lower zone changes as long as the pattern is upper zone predominant.

Diffuse perihilar airspace / ground glass opacity of one or both lungs. Does not include interstitial opacities. This finding can still be predicted if there are other changes as long as the pattern is perihilar predominant.
Cortical breach of the humerus, usually at the surgical neck of humerus.
Cortical breach of a rib without callus formation or union, does not include surgical rib resection or thoracotomy.
Cortical breach of a clavicle. May be difficult to see if nondisplaced. No callus formation for acute fractures.

Loss of joint space, osteophyte formation, sclerosis and degenerative changes of the glenohumeral joint. Usually only predicted if there are significant changes, i.e. near complete loss of joint space.
Humeral head not articulating with glenoid fossa. Typically anterior and inferior dislocation.
Internal fixation of humerus or scapula fractures. May not be predicted if the fracture has been fixated.
Total, partial or reverse total shoulder replacement.
Stents within the trachea or bronchi.
Breast prosthesis usually of gel like material implanted behind or in place of the female breast as cosmetic or reconstructive surgery.
Dilation of the bronchi which can be localised or diffuse.
Multiple large lucencies due to emphysema in the upper and lower zones  of one or both lungs.

Multiple large lucencies due to emphysema in the lower zones of one or both lungs. This finding may still be predicted if there are upper zone changes as long as the pattern is lower zone predominant.

Multiple large lucencies due to emphysema in the upper zones of one or both lungs. This finding may still be predicted if there are lower zone changes as long as the pattern is upper zone predominant.
Calcified soft tissue density in the axilla.
Calcified intraparenchymal lesion or lesions which are smaller than 5mm.
Calcified soft tissue density in the neck.
Calcified thickening along the pleura at the diaphragm, lateral thoracic wall, or apex.
One or more intraparenchymal lesions (>5mm) which may be partially or completely calcified.
Replacement of native cardiac valve. Includes transcatheter aortic valve implantation.
Increased cardiothoracic ratio > 0.5 on PA view and >0.6 on AP view. Includes cardiomegaly and enlarged cardiac silhouette due to pericardial effusion.
Lucent walled lesion which arises from a solid lesion that then develops gas within it. As a result the wall is typically thickened.

note.text: Cavitating mass with content is absent

component.valueString: Collection of air with air fluid level or in crescent shape that separates the wall of a cavity from an inner mass.

The chin is visible and obscuring the apex of the lung or superior mediastinum.
Only the primary AP or PA view is assessed, not the Lateral view or any other view / postprocessed image.
Corticated clavicle fractures with surrounding callus formation or union.
United, malunited or non-united humerus fracture.
Cortical breach of a rib with surrounding callus formation or union.
Internal fixation of clavicle fractures. When a fracture has been fixed, the acute clavicle fracture may not be predicted.

Sclerotic or lytic, malignant or benign lesion within the clavicle with or without pathological fracture. This includes lesions due to systemic conditions such as myeloma, osteogenesis imperfecta, renal osteodystrophy etc.

Left hemidiaphragm is higher than the right or if the right is more than 3cm higher than the left.
This finding should only apply to the inspiratory view, not the lateral or expiratory views.
Abnormal contour of the diaphragm affecting only a segment of the hemidiaphragm.
Pleural masses / opacities in multiple locations. Pleural mass is distinguished from intraparenchymal mass by having an obtuse angle with the pleura.
Flowing osteophytes at the anterior or right lateral vertebral body connecting at least four contiguous vertebrae. Typically, smooth and thin connections.

Pathologically distended small or large bowel loops or stomach. Small bowel loops should measure > 3cm and large bowel loops > 6cm, or if the stomach causes mass effect upon the diaphragm. Air fluid levels may be present on erect view.

Pacemakers, pacing wires (internal or external), internal defibrillators and loop recorders. 
ECG leads do not count as electronic cardiac devices.
Calcified RUQ stones projected over the gallbladder.
Sliding or paraoesophageal hiatus hernia into the posterior mediastinum.  Retrocardiac fluid level may be present.
Increase in size and density of the hila with loss of normal hilar angle.

Sclerotic or lytic, malignant or benign lesion within the humerus with or without pathological fracture. This includes lesions due to systemic conditions such as myeloma, osteogenesis imperfecta, renal osteodystrophy etc.
Increased total lung volumes as evidenced by flattening of the diaphragm or increased retrosternal clear space on lateral view (or both).

Internal jugular lines, subclavian lines and peripheral inserted catheters (PICC).
Central venous lines should be placed with the tip in the SVC / cavoatrial junction. The line should not be in the brachiocephalic, subclavian veins, or right atrium.
Endotracheal or tracheostomy tube within the trachea for ventilation. Needs to be 3 to 7cm above the carina.
Enteric tube from the mouth / nose into the stomach for feeding or drainage.
Pulmonary artery catheter with tip within the pulmonary artery or main pulmonary trunk.
Part of the lungs not included in the image. This finding may be predicted if any image in the series is incomplete.
Masses within the mediastinum with the centre of the mass below the superior border of the aortic arch.

This finding could mean either of the following:
1. Malpositioned intercostal drain: ICC with tip or side holes not within the pleural cavity, typically migrates out into the soft tissue.
2. In position intercostal drain:  Catheter within the pleural space to drain fluid and / or gas.
Non-surgical internal foreign bodies such as inhaled foreign bodies, gunshot shrapnel that is internal to the patient.

Opacities within pulmonary lobules in a linear / branching pattern affecting both upper and lower zones of one or both lungs.   This also includes thickened chronic fibrotic changes from lung scarring.

Opacities within pulmonary lobules in a linear / branching pattern affecting predominantly lower zones of one or both lungs. This also includes thickened chronic fibrotic changes from lung scarring. This finding may still be predicted if there are upper zone changes as long as the pattern is lower zone predominant.

Opacities within pulmonary lobules in a linear / branching pattern affecting predominantly upper zones of one or both lungs. This also includes thickened chronic fibrotic changes from lung scarring. This finding can still be predicted if there are lower zone changes as long as the pattern is upper zone predominant.

note.text: Diffuse fibrotic volume loss is absent

component.valueString: Opacities within pulmonary lobules in a linear / branching pattern affecting one or both lungs. Upper and lower zones affected. Associated with volume loss (hilar displacement, diaphragmatic elevation, tracheal displacement).   This also includes thickened chronic fibrotic changes from lung scarring.

note.text: Lower zone fibrotic volume loss is absent

component.valueString: Opacities within pulmonary lobules in a linear / branching pattern affecting one or both lungs. Lower zone predominant. Associated with volume loss (diaphragmatic elevation).  This also includes thickened chronic fibrotic changes from lung scarring. This finding may still be predicted if there are upper zone changes as long as the pattern is lower zone predominant.

note.text: Upper zone fibrotic volume loss is absent

component.valueString: Opacities within pulmonary lobules in a linear / branching pattern affecting one or both lungs. Upper zone predominant. Has associated volume loss (hilar elevation). This also includes thickened chronic fibrotic changes from lung scarring. Includes apical scarring e.g. from previous TB. This finding can still be predicted if there are lower zone changes as long as the pattern is upper zone predominant.
Increased kyphosis of the thoracic spine with Cobb angle greater than 45 degrees on lateral view. Usually predicted off the lateral view.
Includes subsegmental collapse, linear and bibasal atelectasis.
Fluid within the pleural cavity that is trapped within a fissure or at the apex or lateral wall on an erect view.
Collapse of the entire lung, or most of the lung.

note.text: Post resection volume loss is absent

component.valueString: Post resection volume loss Volume loss due to resection of lung e.g. pneumonectomy, lobectomy or segmentectomy, usually with staples / clips visible
Suture material within then lung parenchyma which is typically post lung resection.
CVC or PICC line where the tip of the catheter is not positioned at the cavoatrial junction or the distal SVC, or if the catheter is looped or kinked.
Endotracheal or tracheostomy tube that is too close to the carina or too far from it (not within 3 to 7cm) , or within a bronchus.
Band around the gastro-oesophageal junction with phi angle between the band and the spine not within 0 to 60 degrees. Malpositioned bands may be associated with oesophageal dilation.

NGT where the tip and the side holes are not projected within the stomach, or the tip of the NGT is not visible and the image is cut-off within 5cm of the gastro-oesophageal junction. May be within the oesophagus or bronchus.
Pulmonary artery catheter with tip not in the main pulmonary trunk or pulmonary arterial branch e.g. in the right ventricle, or if the catheter is looped or kinked.
Absence or asymmetry of breast shadows suggesting mastectomy or partial mastectomy.
Surgical clips in the mediastinum or hilum. Typically small clips from coronary artery bypass grafts. Hilar clips from lung surgery also fall under this category.

note.text: Diffuse nodular / miliary lesions is absent

component.valueString: Multiple tiny lung opacities of one or both lungs. Usually innumerable and too small to measure. May be calcified.

note.text: Multiple masses or nodules is absent

component.valueString: More than one pulmonary mass / nodule.
Any surgical clips in the neck.
Rounded well defined density projected over the expected locations of the nipple, sometimes bilateral.

Severe reduced apparent bone density of the vertebrae such that there is difficulty distinguishing between bone and adjacent soft tissues even when windowing appropriately. Usually predicted off the lateral view.
Unable to see lung markings even after appropriate windowing. Only the primary AP or PA view is assessed, not the Lateral view or any other view / postprocessed image.

The spinous process is laterally displaced by more than a quarter of the interclavicular distance. Only the primary AP or PA view is assessed, not the Lateral view or any other view / postprocessed image. If the patient is severely scoliotic, this finding may be unreliable.
Congenital chest wall deformity with anterior protrusion of the sternum.
Congenital chest wall deformity with concave depression of the sternum.
Thickening of the bronchial wall without dilation of the bronchial lumen.
Fat pad adjacent to the heart border. Can be mistaken for consolidation by referrers.
Unilateral or bilateral fluid within the pleural cavity. May be simple or loculated. May form a meniscus. Present on at least one projection (PA, AP, lateral).

Pleural mass / opacity in one location. Pleural mass is distinguished from intraparenchymal mass by having an obtuse angle with the pleura. A pleural mass is either nodular thickening of the pleura or pleural thickening greater than 1cm. The pleural mass should affect less than half the lung height and unilateral. Local pleural thickening less than 1cm is usually ignored.
Gas within the mediastinum, typically outlining the pericardium and mediastinal margin.
Air within the thoracic cavity outside of the lung. May be associated with lung edge. May have features of tension.
Enlargement of the pulmonary artery typically with loss of the aortopulmonary window.  Width of the right descending pulmonary artery > 17mm on the PA film.
Upper lobe diversion with loss of tapering of vessels towards the apices with upper zone vessels having similar or larger diameter compared to lower zone. Only reliable on erect views.
Internal fixation of rib fractures. May not be predicted if the fracture has been fixated.

Sclerotic or lytic, malignant or benign lesion within the rib with or without pathological fracture. This includes lesions due to systemic conditions such as myeloma, osteogenesis imperfecta, renal osteodystrophy etc. Congenital rib anomalies such as bifid or fused ribs are not included.
Surgical removal of ribs, may be multiple. Typically thoracotomies are performed for lung resection.
Bone anchors within the humeral heads.
Cortical breach of the scapula. This includes both acute and chronic fractures.

Sclerotic or lytic, malignant or benign lesion within the scapula with or without pathological fracture. This includes lesions due to systemic conditions such as myeloma, osteogenesis imperfecta, renal osteodystrophy etc.
Increased lateral curvature of the thoracic spine with Cobb angle greater than 10 degrees on frontal view.
Collapse of entire segment or lobe of the lung, or compressive collapse from adjacent pleural effusion
Fluid within the pleural cavity. In an erect radiograph this accumulates at the base. May form a meniscus.
Air within the thoracic cavity outside of the lung. May be associated with lung edge.
Single rounded well-defined opacity. Measures 3cm or larger.
Single rounded well-defined opacity. Measures less than 3cm.
Internal fixation of the spine for fractures or degeneration.
Near complete loss of intervertebral space, fusion of vertebrae, or heavy calcification of intervertebral discs at multiple levels.

Sclerotic or lytic, malignant or benign lesion within the thoracic spine with or without pathological fracture. This includes lesions due to systemic conditions such as myeloma, osteogenesis imperfecta, renal osteodystrophy etc.

Acute or chronic compression, wedge, distraction or translated fractures. Typically seen on lateral view. Usually chronicity cannot be reliably assessed so this is not differentiated. For compression or wedge fractures, there should be more than 20% loss in anterior height or central height as measured to the nearest normal vertebra or posterior vertebral body height (whichever is larger).
Air within the soft tissues outside the abdominal or thoracic cavity. May be associated with pneumothorax or pneumomediastinum.
Gas below the diaphragm not contained within a lumen.

Masses within the mediastinum with the centre of the mass above the superior border of the aortic arch / loss of paratracheal stripes. If the patient is supine or rotated, the superior mediastinum can be widened due to benign causes such as venous distension or projection.
Air within the thoracic cavity outside of the lung. May be associated with lung edge. Resultant mediastinal shift.

Moving of the trachea across to one side secondary to increased pressure on one side or decreased pressure on the other side. Consideration of the extent of patient rotation must be taken into account.
Outline of any thoracic vertebral bodies not visible. Only the primary AP or PA view is assessed, not the Lateral view or any other view / postprocessed image.
The diaphragm is projected above the 9th posterior rib in a PA view or above the 7th rib in an AP view.
